Target IP: 10.129.206.199

Reconnaissance


I performed a TCP port scan against the target machine using the command sudo nmap -sS 10.129.206.199 -p- and obtained the result shown above. There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP on their standard ports. Time to perform an aggressive scan to identify its services and applications.


I ran the command sudo nmap -sV -A 10.129.206.199 -p 22,80 and obtained the result shown above. The HTTP application on port 80 seems interesting to me. Therefore, I will start enumeration there.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this web application. After some manual enumeration and source-code scanning, I notice there is a portal application to track the bugs. This portal is right next to the Contact button at the top of the webpage.


Pressing the Portal button from the previous image displays the webpage shown above. It informs me to click the here hyperlink to visit the bug bounty tracker system.


And bingo! Now I have access to the bug tracking system as shown above. I filled the inputs with test data and it was output by the tracker system. Time to see how this application works by viewing the source-code.


I viewed the source-code of the log_submit.php page and obtained the result shown above. There is an interesting JavaScript file with the name bountylog.js. This is probably the source-code of the tracking system.


The source code of the bountylog.js is shown above. I notice it seems to be making a POST request to the URL tracker_diRbPr00f314.php. Also, the function bountySubmit() is creating an XML data out of the inputs. Could the application be vulnerable to XML External Entity (XXE) injection attack? Time to fire up burpsuite and test it.


I made a simple POST request using the web application and intercepted the request via burpsuite, as shown above. I notice the data is encoded in URL and then in base64. I will need to find a working payload that will be encoded in the same format. Let's experiment.

I created the payload shown above for the XXE attack. This simple payload will output the contents of the /etc/passwd file inside the title tag. I will need to convert this to base64 and then to URL encoding before sending it to the target machine.


To format the payload, I used Cyberchef as shown above. Firstly, I converted it to base64 and then the URL encoding as shown above. Time to deploy the payload to the target machine.


I intercepted another request and deployed the encoded payload via the burpsuite. And bingo! I was able to successfully read the contents of the /etc/passwd file as shown above. I notice there is a user called development on the target machine. Time to perform a directory search to identify any sensitive files that I can access by using this exploit.

Privilege Escalation


Running the command sudo -l shows this user can execute the binary /usr/bin/python3.8 on the script /opt/skytrain_inc/ticketValidator.py with root privileges. But what does this script do?


Reading through the source-code of the ticketValidator.py script, I noticed the unusual code above. The method evaluate(ticketFile) seems to be making a call to eval. This can lead to command injection attacks! This ticket validator application could be used to perform local privilege escalation. I will need to create a valid ticket with the file type as .md with the following rules:

  1. Valid tickets have to start with the following: # Skytrain Inc
  2. Valid tickets have to contain the string ## Ticket to after the first rule
  3. Valid tickets have to contain the string __Ticket Code:__ after the second rule
  4. Valid tickets have to contain the string ** after the third rule
  5. Valid tickets must follow the fule: the number after the fourth rule until the first + must be an integer that when divided by 7 it has a remainder of 4
  6. And lastly, the validation number after the fifth rule must be greater than 100 to be a valid ticket


I created the ticket shown above by following the validation rules. I created this ticket at /tmp with the filename ticket.md.


I ran the command sudo /usr/bin/python3.8 /opt/skytrain_inc/ticketValidator.py to check the validity. The output was successful and it was valid. Time to exploit the eval function to spawn a shell.


Now my new ticket contains the code __import__('os').system('bash') to spawn a bash shell. This is the only place where I can inject my code as the other rules against string comparison are strict.


And bingo! Now I have a root shell on the target machine. I ran the command sudo /usr/bin/python3.8 /opt/skytrain_inc/ticketValidator.py and the location of the new ticket. Before the ticket is even being validated, a new bash shell is opened. Now I have root privileges on the target machine :) GG.
